<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="116" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,332,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Remarks</emphasis>
. Externally 
<taxonomicName box="[448,555,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thapai">
<emphasis box="[448,555,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. thapai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[612,751,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gillespiei">
<emphasis box="[612,751,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. gillespiei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble each other closely but can be distinguished by the coloration of the median spot on the forewings: the anterior margin of the median spot is dark brown in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gillespiei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. gillespiei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where as it is not so in 
<taxonomicName box="[524,630,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thapai">
<emphasis box="[524,630,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. thapai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They also have different male genitalia: the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1390,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thapai">
<emphasis box="[1284,1390,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. thapai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has basal processes whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[461,591,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gillespei">
<emphasis box="[461,591,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. gillespei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are absent. The females of the two species may also be diagnosed by the shape of the posterior margin of the seventh sternite. In 
<taxonomicName box="[812,917,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thapai">
<emphasis box="[812,917,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. thapai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior margin is shallowly excavated in the middle with lateral rounded lobes whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[710,849,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gillespiei">
<emphasis box="[710,849,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. gillespiei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the excavation is deeper and larger in the form of a trough. Both the species are sympatric.
</paragraph>
